            <section class="mt-10 prose">
              <h2>How the Zombie Apocalypse Survival Calculator Works</h2>
              <p>
                This zombie apocalypse calculator turns your skills, team
                composition, shelter quality, and supplies into a single
                <strong>survival score</strong> for the first 30 days of a
                fictional outbreak. It is designed for fun, storytelling, and
                tabletop RPG planning—not for real emergency prediction.
              </p>

              <h3>The four pillars of survival</h3>
              <p>
                Your overall survival score is built from four pillars, each
                normalized to a 0–100 scale:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Personal skills</strong> – fitness, first aid,
                  navigation, and combat or self-defense.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Team &amp; group</strong> – how many people you have,
                  how balanced their skills are, and how well you cooperate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Shelter &amp; location</strong> – how defensible your
                  base is, how easy it is to escape, and what the surrounding
                  area looks like.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Supplies &amp; logistics</strong> – food, water,
                  medicine, weapons, and how intense the outbreak is in your
                  region.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Conceptual formula (simplified)
                </p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( P \) = personal skills score (0–100)</li>
                  <li>\( T \) = team &amp; group score (0–100)</li>
                  <li>\( S \) = shelter &amp; location score (0–100)</li>
                  <li>\( L \) = supplies &amp; logistics score (0–100)</li>
                  <li>\( I \) = outbreak intensity (1–10)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>We compute a weighted base score:</p>
                <p>\( \text{Base} = 0.30P + 0.20T + 0.25S + 0.25L \)</p>
                <p>Then we apply a penalty for outbreak intensity:</p>
                <p>\( \text{Penalty factor} = 1 - 0.04 \times (I - 5) \)</p>
                <p>Finally, the survival percentage is:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Survival\%} = \min\left(100,\; \max\left(0,\;
                  \text{Base} \times \text{Penalty factor}\right)\right) \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                In practice, the calculator uses slightly more nuanced rules
                (for example, diminishing returns for very large groups and
                extra bonuses for bunkers or remote locations), but the idea is
                the same: strong pillars and a lower-intensity outbreak lead to
                a higher survival chance.
              </p>

              <h3>Risk levels</h3>
              <p>
                Your final percentage is mapped to a qualitative risk level:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>0–25%</strong> – Critical risk: you are very unlikely
                  to survive 30 days without major changes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>26–50%</strong> – High risk: some strengths, but
                  serious weaknesses in at least one pillar.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>51–75%</strong> – Moderate risk: decent odds if you
                  stay cautious and improve your weak spots.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>76–90%</strong> – Low risk: strong preparation and
                  good conditions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>91–100%</strong> – Elite prepper: in this fictional
                  scenario, you are among the best prepared.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Tips to Improve Your Zombie Apocalypse Survival Score</h2>
              <h3>1. Upgrade your personal skills</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Build basic <strong>cardio and strength</strong>—you do not
                  need to be an athlete, but you should be able to run, climb,
                  and carry loads.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Learn <strong>first aid</strong>: bleeding control, wound
                  care, and recognizing dehydration or infection.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Practice <strong>navigation</strong> without GPS: reading
                  maps, using landmarks, and basic compass work.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Study <strong>self-defense</strong> and safe weapon handling
                  (in games or simulations, not real violence).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Build a balanced team</h3>
              <p>
                A group of 3–6 people with complementary skills usually scores
                better than a lone wolf or a huge, chaotic crowd.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Mix roles: medic, scout, mechanic, cook, negotiator, and
                  defender.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Prioritize <strong>trust and communication</strong>—internal
                  conflict is as dangerous as zombies.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Choose and improve your shelter</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Higher floors, solid doors, and limited entry points increase
                  your <strong>security</strong> score.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Multiple exits and good visibility improve your
                  <strong>escape routes</strong> score.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Access to <strong>water sources</strong> (wells, rivers,
                  stored tanks) is critical for long-term survival.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Stock smart supplies</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Water is usually the limiting factor: aim for at least
                  <strong>3 liters per person per day</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Choose <strong>non-perishable food</strong> that is dense in
                  calories and easy to prepare.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Keep a compact <strong>medical kit</strong> with bandages,
                  disinfectant, painkillers, and any essential prescriptions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Tools and weapons should be
                  <strong>reliable and maintainable</strong>, not just flashy.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

              <h3>Is this zombie apocalypse calculator realistic?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Zombies are a fictional threat. The scoring model borrows
                ideas from emergency preparedness, survival games, and disaster
                planning, but it is intentionally simplified and gamified.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for real emergency planning?</h3>
              <p>
                You can use the <em>structure</em>—thinking in terms of skills,
                team, shelter, and supplies—as a starting point for real-world
                preparedness (for example, storms or blackouts). For serious
                planning, always follow guidance from official emergency
                management agencies in your country.
              </p>

              <h3>Why does outbreak intensity reduce my score so much?</h3>
              <p>
                In a high-intensity scenario (global collapse, no functioning
                infrastructure), even well-prepared groups face extreme risk.
                The penalty factor reflects how much harder survival becomes
                when hospitals, police, and supply chains fail.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I tweak the rules for my own game or story?</h3>
